    <fr:title text="Sup Norm">Sup Norm</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The supremum norm (or sup norm) is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002S.xml" addr="FA-002S" title="Norm">norm</fr:link> defined for bounded functions. For a bounded function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: X \rightarrow  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: X \rightarrow  \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, the sup norm is defined as:</fr:p>
    <fr:p>
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{||f||_\infty  = \sup _{x \in  X} |f(x)|}]]></fr:tex>
    </fr:p>
    <fr:p>This norm measures the maximum absolute value that the function takes over its domain.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>In the context of the <fr:link type="external" href="FA-0132">space of continuous functions</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C(X)]]></fr:tex> on a compact space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, the sup norm makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C(X)]]></fr:tex> into a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-002I.xml" addr="FA-002I" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>The sup norm is also used to define the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> space, which consists of essentially bounded <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003D.xml" addr="FA-003D" title="Measurable Function">measurable functions</fr:link>, with the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-003E.xml" addr="FA-003E" title="Essential Supremum">essential supremum</fr:link> replacing the exact supremum.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
